onesia, Iraq, Malaysia, South Africa, and Hawai‘i. With a shared focus on the specific local conditions that influence the ways in which life narratives are told, the authors engage with a variety of academic disciplines, including anthropology, history, media studies, and literature, to challenge claims that life writing is an exclusively Western phenomenon. Addressing the common desire to reflect on lived experience, the authors enlist interdisciplinary perspectives to interrogate the range of cultural forms available for representing and understanding lives.Contributors: Maria Faini, Kenneth George, Philip Holden, David T. Hill, Craig Howes, Bryan Kuwada, Kirin Narayan, Maureen Perkins, Peter Read, Tony Simoes da Silva, Mathilda Slabbert, Gerry van Klinken, Pei-yi Wu.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAutobiographyvCross-cultural studies. 0aBiography as a literary formvCross-cultural studies. 0aBiographyvCross-cultural studies. 0aNational characteristics in literature. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aFaini, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorge, Kenneth M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, David T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolden, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowes, Craig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlinken, Gerry van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuwada, Bryan Kamaoli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNarayan, Kirin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerkins, Maureen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerkins, Maureen, eeditor.4edt4